
<p>You can use the following code to include the C4C Link Bar in a webpage <b>within an iframe</b> (the iframe will be prepended to the body).</p>

<p>In the url you may adjust the page_wrapper_width parameter to match your page wrapper width.</p>

<p>
  You may also set the active tab by setting the active_tab_id parameter to the ID of the tab corresponding to the active tab.<br/>
  e.g. link_bar_tab_1 or link_bar_tab_2 etc.
</p>

<strong>Wordpress instructions:</strong> create a new Widget Widget and copy and paste this code into it</p>

<p style="margin:1em; padding:1em; border:solid black 2px;">
  <small style="font-family:monospace;">

    <%=h "<script type='text/javascript'>" %>

      jQuery(document).ready(function() {
        jQuery("body").prepend("
          <%=h "
            <style type='text/css'>
              #link_bar_frame {
                width:100%;
                height:500px;
                border:none;
                z-index:999;
                position:relative;
                top:0;
                left:0;
              }
              
              #link_bar_frame_wrapper {
                width:100%;
                height:39px;
                background-color:#666766;
              }
            </style>
            
            <div id='link_bar_frame_wrapper'>
              <iframe id='link_bar_frame' scrolling='no' allowtransparency='true' src='#{url_for(:action => :index, :controller => :link_bar, :only_path => false, :page_wrapper_width => @page_wrapper_width, :active_tab_id => @active_tab_id)}'>
              </iframe>
            </div>
          " %>
        ");
      });

    <%=h "</script>" %>

  </small>
</p>
